However, the clinical impressions of many have indicated that oral antibacterial drugs are of benefit in the treatment of acute, severe diarrhea in the calf. If used at all, they should be restricted to acute, severe cases, and they should be given only at the proper dosage for an interval of two to three days. The antibacterials generally thought to be the most clinically beneficial in these cases in our area are the nitrofurans, gentamiein, chloramphenicol, and polymyxin B (
Fig. 1). The dosages used are: nitrofurans (Enterfur*
), two boluses initially, followed by one twice a day per calf; chloramphenicol, 100 mg per kg initially, followed by 50 mg per kg two to three times a day; gentamicin, 2 to 3 mg per kg twice a day; and polymyxin B, 4 to 6 mg per kg twice a day. These drugs were the only ones found by the Kirby-Bauer technique to effectively inhibit in vitro the majority of E. coli isolated from 75 diarrheic calves over a two year period.
